{"title_page": "2019\u201320 Manchester United W.F.C. season", "text_new": "{{Infobox football club season\n| club               = [[Manchester United W.F.C.|Manchester United Women]]\n| season             = 2019\u201320\n| manager            = [[Casey Stoney]]\n| chairman           = [[Joel Glazer|Joel]] and [[Avram Glazer]]\n| chrtitle           = Co-chairmen\n| stadium            = [[Leigh Sports Village]]\n| league             = [[2019\u201320 FA WSL|FA WSL]]\n| league result      = \n| cup1               = [[2019\u201320 Women's FA Cup|FA Cup]]\n| cup1 result        = \n| cup2               = [[2019\u201320 FA Women's League Cup|League Cup]]\n| cup2 result        = \n| league topscorer   = [[Lauren James]] (6)\n| season topscorer   = Lauren James (9)\n| highest attendance = 4,042<br>(vs. [[Manchester City W.F.C.|Manchester City]], 20 October)\n| lowest attendance  = League: 1,707<br>(vs. [[Brighton & Hove Albion W.F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], 24 November)<br>All: 642<br>(vs. [[Brighton & Hove Albion W.F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]], 15 January, [[2019\u201320 FA Women's League Cup|League Cup]])\n| average attendance = {{formatnum:{{#expr: (((2530+2813+1997+1707+1805+2021+1846)/7) round 0)}}}} \n| pattern_la1 = _manutd1920h |pattern_b1 = _mufc1920h |pattern_ra1 = _manutd1920h |pattern_sh1 = _mufc201920h |pattern_so1 = _mufc201920h\n| leftarm1 = E80909 |body1 = E80909 |rightarm1 = E80909 |shorts1 = FFFFFF |socks1 = 000000\n| pattern_la2 = _manutd1920a |pattern_b2 = _mufc201920a |pattern_ra2 = _manutd1920a |pattern_sh2 = _mufc201920a |pattern_so2 = _3_stripes_black\n| leftarm2 = FBEEC4 |body2 = FBEEC4 |rightarm2 = FBEEC4 |shorts2 = 000000 |socks2 = FBEEC4\n| pattern_la3 = _manutd1920t |pattern_b3 = _mufc1920t |pattern_ra3 = _manutd1920t |pattern_sh3 = _manutd1920t |pattern_so3 = _manutd1920t\n| leftarm3 = 000000 |body3 = 000000 |rightarm3 = 000000 |shorts3 = 000000 |socks3 = 000000\n| prevseason = [[2018\u201319 Manchester United W.F.C. season|2018\u201319]]\n| nextseason = \n}}\nThe 2019\u201320 season is [[Manchester United W.F.C.|Manchester United Women's]] second season since they were founded and their first in the [[FA Women's Super League]], the professional top-flight women's league in [[England]]. The club will also compete in the [[Women's FA Cup|FA Cup]] and [[FA Women's League Cup|League Cup]].\n\nFollowing the departure of [[Alex Greenwood]] in August 2019, [[Katie Zelem]] was named as her successor as club captain.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Plant |title=Katie Zelem named as Man Utd Women captain |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-utd-women-announce-new-captain-ahead-of-the-201920-season |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=6 September 2019 |accessdate=6 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\nOn 13 March 2020, in line with the FA's response to the [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]], it was announced the season was temporarily suspended until at least 3 April 2020.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Association |first1=The Football |title=Decision made to postpone professional football until Friday 3 April at the earliest |url=http://www.thefa.com/news/2020/mar/13/fa-premier-league-efl-statement-football-suspended-130320 |website=www.thefa.com}}</ref>\n\n== Pre-season ==\nUnited prepared for their debut season as a top-flight team with their first ever game against foreign opposition, traveling to Norway to play [[Toppserien]] side [[V\u00e5lerenga Fotball Damer|V\u00e5lerenga]] on 31 July, in conjunction with the [[Manchester United F.C.|men's team]] who played in the same city the day before. United also faced Norwegian third division side Sandefjord on 3 August and preceded their trip abroad with a closed-doors friendly at home to [[Blackburn Rovers L.F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]].<ref>{{cite news |title=New friendly dates for Reds and United Women |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/Man-Utd-announce-friendlies-in-Oslo-in-July-for-mens-and-womens-teams |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Manchester United Women arrives at Komplett Arena on Saturday 3 August |url=http://www.sandefjordfotball.no/nyheter/manchester-united-women-kommer-til-komplett-arena-lordag-3.august |website=sandefjordfotball.no |language=Norwegian }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Dates for your diary |url=https://www.rovers.co.uk/news/2019/june/dates-for-your-diary2/ |website=rovers.co.uk }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Opponents \n!H / A\n!Result<br />F\u2013A\n!Scorers\n!Attendance\n|- bgcolor=#C0C0C0\n|24 July 2019\n|[[Blackburn Rovers L.F.C.|Blackburn Rovers]]\n|H\n|colspan=\"3\"|Behind closed doors, no official scoreline\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|31 July 2019\n|[[V\u00e5lerenga Fotball Damer|V\u00e5lerenga]]\n|[[Intility Arena|A]]\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/valerenga-v-man-united-women-friendly-match-report 1\u20134]\n|[[Jessica Sigsworth|Sigsworth]] 24'\n|7,124\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|3 August 2019\n|[[Sandefjord Fotball|Sandefjord]]\n|[[Komplett Arena|A]]\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-sandefjord-v-man-united-women-3-august-2019 5\u20130]\n|[[Mollie Green|Green]] 12', [[Ella Toone|Toone]] 35', [[Jane Ross (footballer)|Ross]] 40', [[Hayley Ladd|Ladd]] 61', [[Jessica Sigsworth|Sigsworth]] 67'\n|\n|}\n\n== FA Women's Super League ==\n{{main|2019\u201320 FA WSL}}\n\nFollowing a successful [[2018\u201319 Manchester United W.F.C. season|debut season]] in the [[FA Women's Championship]], Manchester United earned promotion to the [[FA Women's Super League]]. On 10 May 2019, [[The Football Association|the FA]] confirmed Manchester United had been granted a license to compete in the WSL for the [[2019\u201320 FA WSL|2019\u201320 season]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://womenscompetitions.thefa.com/en/Article/man-utd-tottenham-fa-wsl-100519|title=Man Utd and Spurs promoted|website=TheFA.com}}</ref>\n\n=== Results summary ===\n{{Fb_rs|hw=5|hd=0|hl=2|hgf=14|hga=3|aw=2|ad=2|al=3|agf=10|aga=9}}\n{{Fb rs footer|u=23 February 2020|s=[http://www.fawsl.com/stats.html FA WSL]|date=April 2020}}\n\n===Matches===\nThe opening weekend WSL fixtures were announced on 1 July 2019 and included the first [[Manchester derby#Women's football|Manchester derby]] between the two women's teams with the fixture being played at the [[City of Manchester Stadium]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Women's Super League: Manchester City face Manchester United on 2019-20 opening day |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/48823671 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=6 July 2019 |date=1 July 2019}}</ref> The remaining league fixtures were announced on 10 July 2019.<ref>{{cite news |first=Michael |last=Plant |title=United Women's WSL fixtures for 2019/20 |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/manchester-united-women-2019-20-wsl-fixtures-released |website=ManUtd.com |publisher=Manchester United |date=10 July 2019 |accessdate=8 September 2019 }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Opponents\n!H / A\n!Result<br />F\u2013A\n!Scorers\n!Attendance\n!League<br />position\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|7 September 2019\n|[[Manchester City W.F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-for-man-city-women-v-man-united-women-on-7-september-2019 0\u20131]\n|\n|31,213\n|11th\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|16 September 2019\n|[[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-united-women-v-arsenal-women-match-report-16-september-2019 0\u20131]\n|\n|2,530\n|12th\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|28 September 2019\n|[[Liverpool F.C. Women|Liverpool]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/manchester-united-women-2-liverpool-0-match-report-28-sep-2019 2\u20130]\n|[[Lauren James|James]] 71', [[Katie Zelem|Zelem]] 90+5' ([[Penalty kick (association football)|pen.]])\n|2,813\n|6th\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|13 October 2019\n|[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Women|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/tottenham-hotspur-women-v-man-utd-women-match-report-13-october-2019 3\u20130]\n|[[Kirsty Hanson|Hanson]] 13', [[Ashleigh Neville|Neville]] 52' ([[Own goal|o.g.]]), [[Jane Ross (footballer)|Ross]] 90+2'\n|1,299\n|4th\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|27 October 2019\n|[[Reading F.C. Women|Reading]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-for-man-united-women-v-reading-women-on-27-october-2019 2\u20130]\n|[[Kirsty Hanson|Hanson]] 16', [[Jessica Sigsworth|Sigsworth]] 85'\n|1,997\n|4th\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|17 November 2019\n|[[Chelsea F.C. Women|Chelsea]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/Match-report-for-Chelsea-Women-v-Man-United-Women-on-17-November-2019 0\u20131]\n|\n|4,790\n|5th\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|24 November 2019\n|[[Brighton & Hove Albion W.F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-for-man-united-women-v-brighton-and-hove-albion-women-on-24-november-2019 4\u20130]\n|[[Lauren James|James]] 10', [[Leah Galton|Galton]] (2) 29', 67', [[Katie Zelem|Zelem]] 87' ([[Penalty kick (association football)|pen.]])\n|1,707\n|5th\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|1 December 2019\n|[[West Ham United F.C. Women|West Ham United]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/west-ham-v-man-utd-women-match-report 2\u20133]\n|[[Kirsty Hanson|Hanson]] 1', [[Lauren James|James]] 80'\n|1,736\n|5th\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|8 December 2019\n|[[Everton F.C. (Women)|Everton]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-from-man-united-women-v-everton 3\u20131]\n|[[Lauren James|James]] (2) 4', 45', [[Katie Zelem|Zelem]] 11' ([[Penalty kick (association football)|pen.]]) \n|1,805\n|4th\n|- bgcolor=#C0C0C0\n|15 December 2019\n|[[Birmingham City W.F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n|A\n|P\u2013P\n|colspan=\"3\"|Postponed due to waterlogged pitch\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|5 January 2020\n|[[Bristol City W.F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-for-manchester-united-women-v-bristol-city-on-5-january-2020 0\u20131]\n|\n|2,021\n|4th\n|- bgcolor=#C0C0C0\n|12 January 2020\n|[[Liverpool F.C. Women|Liverpool]]\n|A\n|P\u2013P\n|colspan=\"3\"|Postponed due to waterlogged pitch\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|19 January 2020\n|[[Tottenham Hotspur F.C. Women|Tottenham Hotspur]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/womens-super-league-match-report-man-united-v-tottenham-19-jan-20 3\u20130]\n|[[Katie Zelem|Zelem]] (2) 58' ([[Penalty kick (association football)|pen.]]), 87', [[Jessica Sigsworth|Sigsworth]] 65'\n|1,846\n|4th\n|- bgcolor=#ffffcc\n|2 February 2020\n|[[Reading F.C. Women|Reading]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-for-reading-women-v-man-united-women-on-2-february 1\u20131]\n|[[Lauren James|James]] 30'\n|1,256\n|4th\n|- bgcolor=#C0C0C0\n|9 February 2020\n|[[Chelsea F.C. Women|Chelsea]]\n|H\n|P\u2013P\n|colspan=\"3\"|All WSL games postponed due to [[Storm Ciara]]<ref>{{cite web |last1=Duncker |first1=Charlotte |title=Manchester United vs Chelsea in WSL postponed due to Storm Ciara |url=https://www.manchestereveningnews.co.uk/sport/football/man-utd-women-chelsea-postponed-17716267 |website=Manchester Evening News |date=9 February 2020}}</ref>\n|- bgcolor=#ffffcc\n|12 February 2020\n|[[Brighton & Hove Albion W.F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/Womens-Super-League-match-report-Brighton-v-Man-Utd-12-Feb-2020 1\u20131]\n|[[Megan Walsh (footballer)|Walsh]] 1' ([[Own goal|o.g.]])\n|903\n|5th\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|23 February 2020\n|[[Everton F.C. (Women)|Everton]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/womens-super-league-match-report-everton-v-man-united-23-feb-2020 3\u20132]\n|[[Leah Galton|Galton]] (2) 21', 29', [[Ella Toone|Toone]] 63'\n|893\n|4th\n|- bgcolor=#C0C0C0\n|22 March 2020\n|[[West Ham United F.C. Women|West Ham United]]\n|H\n|P\u2013P\n|colspan=\"3\" rowspan=\"3\"|The FA postponed all professional leagues due to [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United Kingdom|coronavirus pandemic]]\n|- bgcolor=#C0C0C0\n|25 March 2020\n|[[Birmingham City W.F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n|A\n|P\u2013P\n|- bgcolor=#C0C0C0\n|28 March 2020\n|[[Manchester City W.F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|H\n|P\u2013P\n|-\n|5 April 2020\n|[[Arsenal W.F.C.|Arsenal]]\n|A\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|25 April 2020\n|[[Bristol City W.F.C.|Bristol City]]\n|A\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|3 May 2020\n|[[Liverpool F.C. Women|Liverpool]]\n|A\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|12 May 2020\n|[[Chelsea F.C. Women|Chelsea]]\n|H\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|-\n|16 May 2020\n|[[Birmingham City W.F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n|H\n|\n|\n|\n|\n|}\n\n=== League table ===\n{{2019-20 FA WSL table|showteam=MNU}}\n\n== Women's FA Cup ==\n{{main|2019\u201320 Women's FA Cup}}\nManchester United entered the Women's FA Cup in the fourth round with the rest of the top two tiers and were drawn against [[Manchester City W.F.C.|Manchester City]], one of only two all-WSL ties of the round. It was the third time the [[Manchester derby#Women's football|derby]] rivals had met in the 2019\u201320 season having already faced off in the league and [[2019\u201320 FA Women's League Cup#Group C|League Cup]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thefa.com/competitions/womens/the-womens-fa-cup/more/round-dates|title=Women's FA Cup dates|website=TheFA.com|publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> The match was selected as the televised game of the round live on the [[BBC Red Button]] and subsequently rescheduled from the typical Sunday when the rest of the round's fixtures were played, to the preceding Saturday.<ref>{{cite web |title=SheBelieves Cup & Women's FA Cup ties to be broadcast live on the BBC |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/51180761 |website=BBC Sport |date=20 January 2020}}</ref> City won 3\u20132 with goals from [[England women's national football team|England]] internationals [[Ellen White (footballer)|Ellen White]] and [[Jill Scott (footballer)|Jill Scott]] proving the difference while a controversial no-goal decision put the lack of [[goal-line technology]] in women's football under scrutiny.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Wrack |first1=Suzanne |title=Manchester United rue lack of tech support as City win FA Cup derby |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2020/jan/25/manchester-united-women-manchester-city-women-fa-cup-match-report |website=The Observer |date=25 January 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Whyatt |first1=Katie |title=Lack of technology in women's football under scrutiny after Manchester United's contentious FA Cup exit to Manchester City |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/football/2020/01/25/lack-technology-womens-football-scrutiny-manchester-uniteds/ |website=The Telegraph |date=25 January 2020}}</ref> It marked the first time Manchester United had lost the first knockout game of either domestic cup competition at the fourth attempt.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Round\n!Opponents\n!H / A\n!Result<br />F\u2013A\n!Scorers\n!Attendance\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|25 January 2020\n|Round 4\n|[[Manchester City W.F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-utd-women-v-man-city-women-match-report-25-january-2020 2\u20133]\n|[[Lauren James|James]] 69', [[Lauren Hemp|Hemp]] 88' ([[Own goal|o.g.]])\n|1,948\n|}\n\n== FA Women's League Cup ==\n{{main|2019\u201320 FA Women's League Cup}}\n\n=== Group stage ===\nManchester United were entered into Group C for the 2019\u201320 League Cup alongside fellow [[FA Women's Super League|WSL]] teams Birmingham City, Everton and Manchester City, and [[FA Women's Championship|Championship]] side Leicester City.<ref>{{cite web |title=Continental League Cup groups |url=https://womenscompetitions.thefa.com/en/Article/continental-cup-groups-260719 |website=TheFA.com |publisher=The Football Association}}</ref> On 21 November 2019, United defeated [[Leicester City W.F.C.|Leicester City]] 11\u20131 to set a new club record home win and the second largest margin of victory in the competition's history, bettered only by [[Chelsea F.C. Women|Chelsea]]'s 13\u20130 victory over [[London Bees]] in [[2014 FA WSL#FA WSL Cup|2014]]. [[Ella Toone]] also matched the club record for goals in a single game with five.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Plant |first1=Michael |title=Man Utd Women v Leicester Women match report 21 November 2019 |url=https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/Man-Utd-Women-v-Leicester-Women-match-report-21-November-2019 |website=ManUtd.com |accessdate=22 November 2019 |date=21 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Women's Continental League Cup: Manchester United beat 11\u20131 Leicester City in group stage |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/50423397 |website=BBC Sport |accessdate=22 November 2019 |date=21 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Opponents\n!H / A\n!Result<br />F\u2013A\n!Scorers\n!Attendance\n!Group<br />position\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|20 October 2019\n|[[Manchester City W.F.C.|Manchester City]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-utd-women-v-man-city-women-match-report 2\u20130]\n|[[Katie Zelem|Zelem]] 7', [[Jessica Sigsworth|Sigsworth]] 54'\n|4,042\n|3rd\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|3 November 2019\n|[[Everton F.C. (Women)|Everton]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/everton-women-v-man-utd-women-match-report-3-november-2019 3\u20130]\n|[[Lauren James|James]] 22', [[Katie Zelem|Zelem]] 78' ([[Penalty kick (association football)|pen.]]), [[Amy Turner (footballer)|A. Turner]] 87'\n|361\n|1st\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|21 November 2019\n|[[Leicester City W.F.C.|Leicester City]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/Man-Utd-Women-v-Leicester-Women-match-report-21-November-2019 11\u20131]\n|[[Jessica Sigsworth|Sigsworth]] 2', [[Lizzie Arnot|Arnot]] 7', [[Ella Toone|Toone]] (5) 21', 43', 45', 73', 87', [[Kirsty Smith|Smith]] 40', [[Jane Ross (footballer)|Ross]] 70', [[Hayley Ladd|Ladd]] 83', [[Lauren James|James]] 90+1'\n|1,127\n|1st\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|11 December 2019\n|[[Birmingham City W.F.C.|Birmingham City]]\n|A\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/match-report-for-birmingham-city-women-v-united-women-on-11-december-2019 3\u20131]\n|[[Lizzie Arnot|Arnot]] 1', [[Jane Ross (footballer)|Ross]] 27', [[Ella Toone|Toone]] 90+3'\n|442\n|1st\n|}\n{{2019\u201320 FA WSL Cup Group C table|showteam=MNU}}\n\n=== Knockout phase ===\nUnited qualified top of their group for the second consecutive season, guaranteeing themselves a quarter-final home tie in the process. A 2\u20131 win over [[Brighton & Hove Albion W.F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]] saw United reach the semi-final stage for the second consecutive season, setting up a home tie with [[Chelsea F.C. Women|Chelsea]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!Date\n!Round\n!Opponents\n!H / A\n!Result<br />F\u2013A\n!Scorers\n!Attendance\n|- bgcolor=#ddffdd\n|15 January 2020\n|Quarter-final\n|[[Brighton & Hove Albion W.F.C.|Brighton & Hove Albion]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/man-utd-women-v-brighton-women-match-report-15-january-2020 2\u20131]\n|[[Abbie McManus|McManus]] 13', [[Jane Ross (footballer)|Ross]] 75'\n|642\n|- bgcolor=#ffdddd\n|29 January 2020\n|Semi-final\n|[[Chelsea F.C. Women|Chelsea]]\n|H\n|[https://www.manutd.com/en/news/detail/womens-match-report-man-united-0-chelsea-1-continental-league-cup 0\u20131]\n|\n|1,044\n|}\n\n== Squad statistics ==\n{{see also|List of Manchester United W.F.C. records and statistics}}\n{{updated|matches played 23 February 2020}}\n:Numbers in parentheses denote appearances as [[substitute (association football)|substitute]].\n:Key to positions: GK&nbsp;\u2013 [[Goalkeeper (association football)|Goalkeeper]]; DF&nbsp;\u2013 [[Defender (association football)|Defender]]; MF&nbsp;\u2013 [[Midfielder]]; FW&nbsp;\u2013 [[Forward (association football)|Forward]]\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n!rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"bottom\"|No.\n!rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"bottom\"|Pos.\n!rowspan=\"2\" valign=\"bottom\"|Name\n!colspan=