 All 45 elected members were [[Independent (politician)|independents]].\n\nThe Elections Ordinance, 2004 <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.guernseylegalresources.gg/CHttpHandler.ashx?id=69365&p=0 |title=Ordinance of the States VI 2004}}</ref>\n\n==Overall Results==\n{{Guernsey States election, 2004}}\n\n==Results==\n\nSt Peter Port North District\n* Leon Gallienne\n* [[Wendy Morgan (politician)|Wendy Morgan]]\n* Rhoderick Matthews\n* Jack Honeybill\n* [[Diane Lewis (Guernsey legislator)|Diane Lewis]]\n* Chris Brock \n* Jean Pritchard\n\n{{col-start}}\n{{col-2}}\nSt Peter Port South District\n* [[Laurie Morgan]]\n* John Gollop\n* Brian Gabriel\n* Barry Brehaut \n* Carla McNaulty Bauer\n* Michael Burbridge (dec)\n* Jenny Tasker (elected in 2005 by-election)\n\nWest District\n* Peter Sirett\n* Martin Ozanne\n* Claire Waite\n* David Grut\n* David De Lisle\n* Al Brouard\n\nSouth East District\n* Francis Quinn\n* Janine Le Sauvage\n* William Bell\n* [[Mike Torode|Michael Torode]]\n* Charles Parkinson\n* Mike O'Hara\n\n{{Col-2}}\nVale District\n* Peter Roffey\n* Mary Lowe\n* David Jones\n* Graham Guille\n* Brian de Jersey\n* Geoff Mahy\n* Duncan Staples\n\nSt Sampson's District\n* Samantha Maindonald\n* [[Lyndon Trott]]\n* Ivan Rihoy\n* Daniel Le Cheminant\n* Ron Le Moignan\n* Scott Ogier\n\nCastel District\n* Alexander Adam\n* Eric Walters\n* Bernard Flouquet\n* Thomas Le Pelley\n* Jonathan Le Tocq\n* Stuart Falla\n* Mark Dorey\n{{col-end}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Politics of Guernsey]]\n* [[Elections in Guernsey]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Guernsey elections}}\n\n[[Category:Elections in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:2004 elections in Europe]]\n[[Category:2004 in Guernsey]]\n[[Category:April 2004 events in Europe]]\n", "name_user": "D Eaketts", "label": "safe", "comment": "Filled in 1 bare reference(s) with reFill 2", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/2004_Guernsey_general_election"}
{"title_page": "Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage", "text_new": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = BerkeleyCastle WestVirginia.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= WV 9, [[Berkeley Springs, West Virginia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|39|37|38|N|78|13|49|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin                 = Eastern Panhandle of West Virginia#West Virginia#USA\n| map_label                = Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage\n  | area =\n  | built =1885\n  | architect= [[Alfred B. Mullett|Mullett, A.B.]] and [[Snowden Ashford|Ashford, Snowden]]\n  | architecture= Late Victorian\n  | added = November 28, 1980<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=80004035\n}}\n\nThe '''Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage''', also known as the '''Berkeley Castle''', is located on a hill above [[Berkeley Springs, West Virginia|Berkeley Springs]], [[West Virginia]]. The castle-like house was built for Colonel [[Samuel Taylor Suit]] of [[Washington, D.C.]] as a personal retreat near the spa town, beginning in 1885.  It was not complete by the time of his death in 1888 and was finished in the early 1890s for his widow, Rosa Pelham Suit, whom Suit had first met at Berkeley Springs. The post 1888 work is of noticeably inferior quality.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Nomination: Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage|url=http://www.wvculture.org/shpo/nr/pdf/morgan/80004035.pdf |format=pdf|date=July 10, 1980 |author=Rodney S. Collins|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n\nThe fifteen-room interior features a ballroom {{convert|50|ft|m|1}} wide and {{convert|40|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} long. The design is attributed to Washington architect [[Alfred B. Mullett]], who is alleged to have drawn a rough sketch of the plan on a tablecloth at the Berkeley Springs Hotel. The design may have been based on elements of [[Berkeley Castle]] in [[Gloucestershire]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/census_then_now/suitland_md/colonel_suit.html|title=Colonel Suit|work=History|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref> Detailed design and construction supervision was carried out by [[Snowden Ashford]], who designed Washington's [[Eastern Market, Washington, D.C.|Eastern Market]], apprenticed for Mullett and is also credited as an architect.<ref name=\"FOHB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fohbc.com/PDF_Files/STSuit_JSullivan.pdf|title=The Life and Loves of S.T. Suit: A Jug-Filler's Story|last=Sullian|first=Jack|date=Spring 2005|work=Bottles and Extras|publisher=Federation of Historic Bottle Collectors|pages=66\u201369|accessdate=2009-02-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920012039/http://fohbc.com/PDF_Files/STSuit_JSullivan.pdf|archive-date=2010-09-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Mrs. Suit entertained lavishly at the house until her money ran out and the property was sold in 1913.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\n=== Purchase by the VDare Foundation. ===\nIn February 2020, the property was purchased by the immigration-focused organization [[VDARE|The VDARE Foundation]].  The VDARE foundation is the publisher of the website VDARE.com which self describes their mission as \"education on two main issues: first, the unsustainability of current US immigration policy and second, the \u201cNational Question,\u201d which is the viability of the US as a nation-state.  We do this through the VDARE.com webzine and VDARE Books, public speaking, conferences, debates and media appearances.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vdare.com/about|title=About|website=VDARE.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>   VDare is described by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]]  as \"a place where relatively intellectually inclined leaders of the anti-immigrant movement share their opinions. VDARE.com also regularly publishes articles by prominent white nationalists, race scientists and anti-Semites.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/group/vdare|title=VDARE|website=Southern Poverty Law Center|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>  VDARE founder and editor [[Peter Brimelow]] stated \u201cWe absolutely will not be having rallies, marches or demonstrations. We\u2019ve never been involved in anything like that, and we never will be,\u201d and \u201cWe just want to be quiet, good neighbors.  \u201cThe only public events we\u2019re anticipating right now are the local charitable functions that we understand the castle has traditionally hosted. We hope to have some private meetings and functions, but don\u2019t have plans for any public VDARE events.\u201d<ref name=\"heraldmail\">{{cite news |last1=Vincent |first1=Jenni |title=Foundation focused on immigration buys Berkeley Springs castle for $1.4M |url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/tri_state/west_virginia/foundation-focused-on-immigration-buys-berkeley-springs-castle-for-m/article_7adcf945-4fce-554e-8dd9-987058af198f.html |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=Herald Mail Media |date=25 February 2020}}</ref>  VDARE purchased the house for $1.4 million and the source of the money is unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2020/03/19/west-virginia-tourist-hub-rejects-vdares-negative-message|title=West Virginia Tourist Hub Rejects VDARE\u2019s \u2018Negative\u2019 Message|last=|first=|date=|website=Southern Poverty Law Center|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage}}\n* [http://www.berkeleyspringscastle.org/castle/BerkeleySpringsCastle.html Berkeley Springs Castle]\n\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suit, Samuel Taylor, Cottage}}\n[[Category:Bath (Berkeley Springs), West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Castles in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1891]]\n[[Category:Houses in Morgan County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Morgan County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Stone houses in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Victorian architecture in West Virginia]]\n\n\n{{WestVirginia-NRHP-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox NRHP | name =Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage\n  | nrhp_type = \n  | image = BerkeleyCastle WestVirginia.jpg\n  | caption = \n  | location= WV 9, [[Berkeley Springs, West Virginia]]\n  | coordinates = {{coord|39|37|38|N|78|13|49|W|display=inline,title}}\n| locmapin                 = Eastern Panhandle of West Virginia#West Virginia#USA\n| map_label                = Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage\n  | area =\n  | built =1885\n  | architect= [[Alfred B. Mullett|Mullett, A.B.]] and [[Snowden Ashford|Ashford, Snowden]]\n  | architecture= Late Victorian\n  | added = November 28, 1980<ref name=\"nris\">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref>\n  | governing_body = Private\n  | refnum=80004035\n}}\n\nThe '''Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage''', also known as the '''Berkeley Castle''', is located on a hill above [[Berkeley Springs, West Virginia|Berkeley Springs]], [[West Virginia]]. The castle-like house was built for Colonel [[Samuel Taylor Suit]] of [[Washington, D.C.]] as a personal retreat near the spa town, beginning in 1885.  It was not complete by the time of his death in 1888 and was finished in the early 1890s for his widow, Rosa Pelham Suit, whom Suit had first met at Berkeley Springs. The post 1888 work is of noticeably inferior quality.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\">{{Cite journal|title=National Register of Historic Places Nomination: Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage|url=http://www.wvculture.org/shpo/nr/pdf/morgan/80004035.pdf |format=pdf|date=July 10, 1980 |author=Rodney S. Collins|publisher=National Park Service}}</ref>\n\nThe fifteen-room interior features a ballroom {{convert|50|ft|m|1}} wide and {{convert|40|ft|m|1|abbr=on}} long. The design is attributed to Washington architect [[Alfred B. Mullett]], who is alleged to have drawn a rough sketch of the plan on a tablecloth at the Berkeley Springs Hotel. The design may have been based on elements of [[Berkeley Castle]] in [[Gloucestershire]], [[United Kingdom]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.census.gov/history/www/census_then_now/suitland_md/colonel_suit.html|title=Colonel Suit|work=History|publisher=U.S. Census Bureau|accessdate=2011-11-22}}</ref> Detailed design and construction supervision was carried out by [[Snowden Ashford]], who designed Washington's [[Eastern Market, Washington, D.C.|Eastern Market]], apprenticed for Mullett and is also credited as an architect.<ref name=\"FOHB\">{{cite web|url=http://www.fohbc.com/PDF_Files/STSuit_JSullivan.pdf|title=The Life and Loves of S.T. Suit: A Jug-Filler's Story|last=Sullian|first=Jack|date=Spring 2005|work=Bottles and Extras|publisher=Federation of Historic Bottle Collectors|pages=66\u201369|accessdate=2009-02-10|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100920012039/http://fohbc.com/PDF_Files/STSuit_JSullivan.pdf|archive-date=2010-09-20|url-status=dead}}</ref>  Mrs. Suit entertained lavishly at the house until her money ran out and the property was sold in 1913.<ref name=\"nrhpinv2\"/>\n\nThe cottage remains privately owned. In February 2020, the property was purchased by the immigration-focused organization [[VDARE|The VDARE Foundation]].  The VDARE foundation is the publisher of the website VDARE.com which self describes their mission as \"education on two main issues: first, the unsustainability of current US immigration policy and second, the \u201cNational Question,\u201d which is the viability of the US as a nation-state.  We do this through the VDARE.com webzine and VDARE Books, public speaking, conferences, debates and media appearances.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://vdare.com/about|title=About|website=VDARE.com|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>   VDare is described by the [[Southern Poverty Law Center]]  as \"a place where relatively intellectually inclined leaders of the anti-immigrant movement share their opinions. VDARE.com also regularly publishes articles by prominent white nationalists, race scientists and anti-Semites.\"<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/fighting-hate/extremist-files/group/vdare|title=VDARE|website=Southern Poverty Law Center|language=en|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>  VDARE founder and editor [[Peter Brimelow]] stated \u201cWe absolutely will not be having rallies, marches or demonstrations. We\u2019ve never been involved in anything like that, and we never will be,\u201d and \u201cWe just want to be quiet, good neighbors.  \u201cThe only public events we\u2019re anticipating right now are the local charitable functions that we understand the castle has traditionally hosted. We hope to have some private meetings and functions, but don\u2019t have plans for any public VDARE events.\u201d<ref name=\"heraldmail\">{{cite news |last1=Vincent |first1=Jenni |title=Foundation focused on immigration buys Berkeley Springs castle for $1.4M |url=https://www.heraldmailmedia.com/news/tri_state/west_virginia/foundation-focused-on-immigration-buys-berkeley-springs-castle-for-m/article_7adcf945-4fce-554e-8dd9-987058af198f.html |accessdate=26 February 2020 |work=Herald Mail Media |date=25 February 2020}}</ref>  VDARE purchased the house for $1.4 million and the source of the money is unknown.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.splcenter.org/hatewatch/2020/03/19/west-virginia-tourist-hub-rejects-vdares-negative-message|title=West Virginia Tourist Hub Rejects VDARE\u2019s \u2018Negative\u2019 Message|last=|first=|date=|website=Southern Poverty Law Center|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category-inline|Samuel Taylor Suit Cottage}}\n* [http://www.berkeleyspringscastle.org/castle/BerkeleySpringsCastle.html Berkeley Springs Castle]\n\n\n{{National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia}}\n\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Suit, Samuel Taylor, Cottage}}\n[[Category:Bath (Berkeley Springs), West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Castles in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1891]]\n[[Category:Houses in Morgan County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Houses on the National Register of Historic Places in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:National Register of Historic Places in Morgan County, West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Stone houses in West Virginia]]\n[[Category:Victorian architecture in West Virginia]]\n\n\n{{WestVirginia-NRHP-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Geo8rge", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Samuel_Taylor_Suit_Cottage"}
